1. Rearrange the NMR frequency formula to solve for the gyromagnetic ratio (γ):
   \[
   γ = \frac{2πν}{B}
   \]

2. Substitute the given values into the formula:
   \[
   γ = \frac{2π \times 115.5 \text{ MHz}}{20.0 \text{ T}}
   \]

3. Calculate the gyromagnetic ratio (γ):
   \[
   γ = \frac{2π \times 115.5 \times 10^6 \text{ Hz}}{20.0 \text{ T}}
   \]
   \[
   γ = \frac{2π \times 115.5 \times 10^6}{20.0}
   \]
   \[
   γ = \frac{2 \times 3.14159 \times 115.5 \times 10^6}{20.0}
   \]
   \[
   γ ≈ \frac{725.6 \times 10^6}{20.0}
   \]
   \[
   γ ≈ 36.28 \times 10^6 \text{ rad T}^{-1} \text{ s}^{-1}
   \]

